tianity's link to Judaism while also respecting the independent religious identity of Jews. Through a fresh study of Origen's allegorical interpretation, this book challenges the common charge that Christian non-literal reading of scripture necessarily undermines the literal meaning of the text. This highly interdisciplinary work will advance debates about different methods of interpretation and about different types of textual meaning that are relevant for many disciplines, including ancient Christianity, Jewish and Christian thought, literary theory, religious studies, and classical studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aChristianity and other religionsxJudaism. 0aJudaismxRelationsxChristianity. 7aRELIGION / Antiquities & Archaeology.2bisacsh  aallegory.  abiblical interpretation.  abiblical scholar.  achristian thinkers.  achristian tradition.  achristianity.  achurch doctrine.  achurch fathers.  aclassical studies.  acovenant.  adaniel boyarin.  aerich auerbach.  afigural reading.  ahans frei.  ahebrew scripture.  ahermeneutics.  ajewish thinkers.  ajudaism.  anew testament.  anonfiction.  aold testament.  areligion.  areligious identity.  areligious studies.  ascripture.  aspirituality.  atheology.  atorah.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092598440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520925984423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520925984/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles